131076;instagram;2018-11-28 13:07:46;FALSE;hi everyone! my name is kristine and i am so excited to be taking over we are herâ€™s insta account!! so a little about me. when i was a freshman in college
column3: i was raped in the woods and left on the side of the road. my story became public from the very beginning. a woman who i donâ€™t even know
column5: called 911 when she saw me fall out of my perpetratorâ€™s car.

column2: and i now was a 19 year old college freshman that had to try to get back to some kind of normalcy and work with the police and district attorney to convict my perpetrator.

column1: if i would have known then what i know now
column2: i would have known there was no way to get back to what i thought was normal and i had to learn to create a new normal. i also would have told myself
column3: that i needed to learn to love myself in order to move forward instead of going out and searching for whomever would love me. but i learned the hard way.
suffered from bulimia nervosa for 4 years after my rape and continued to have self-doubt and blamed myself.

column1: i will say that i am still healing today but the positives in my life weigh out the negative and i have been able to learn how to manage my triggers.
i also went through three serious relationships until i finally met my husband. he is such a driving force behind my healing and has continued to support me on how i need to heal.

column1: 131152;instagram;2018-11-29 12:54:17;FALSE;"""the left could do worse than admit that it has given the right considerable material to work with. itâ€™s not plausible to condemn trumpâ€™s misogyny without some self-interrogation as to how a celebrated film producer such as harvey weinstein managed to continue being a prominent donor to liberal causes and the democratic party when claims of his serial sexual harassment and alleged rapes were an open secret""
a classic case of ""we will deal with women's rights after we win the revolution""

it is indeed appalling how misogyny and gender based violence against women in the workplace has been routinely ignored and dismisses.  transactional sex became normalised in many industries. it was almost the price of entry into the boys club of public enterprise and industry. if you want to be safe stay at home like a good little woman - it seemed to stay.
i'm many cases replicating the paternalism of the wealthy along gender lines. or as we feminists would call it - thats the patriarchy.
it's time for a change. it's time to change. and this is the opportunity for change. we have to move from toxic cynicism and disillusionment  to healthy scepticism and confidence.

the proposed  ilo convention to end gbv in the workplace needs advocacy and implementing partners. if you're concerned for workers rights and women's workplace safety the convention will provide global standards that you can hold your employers and governments to.

column1: the woman in this photo is a fighter. she's a survivor. she is me. and i'm so proud of me.

column3: i was sexually assaulted by a fellow service member who i deployed with. someone i was supposed to trust. a brother in arms. and i buried it. yes
column7: i blamed myself and buried it. for a year and a half
column8: i convinced myself i was responsible for my own assault. i blamed myself for someone else violating me. i began therapy for the assault
column9: but i didn't want to deal with the assault
column10: so i kept cancelling the appointments. i was forced to stop avoiding and confront my demons quite forcibly on 16oct18.

column2: i told my sergeant that when i got home
column3: i was going to kill myself. to which my sergeant said
column5: you're not going home."" i was checked in to the psychiatric facility in our hospital
column6: then transferred to a civilian facility with a special ward specifically for military sexual traumas. and when you're in an inpatient facility
column7: you're really not allowed to avoid things. and so i dealt with it. i broke. i cried. i got pissed. and then

column1: this picture is the first time i've been in the gym since 16oct18. the first time i've been able to lose myself in a workout
column2: to sweat everything out. and the first chance to start the journey for become as strong physically as i am now mentally.

column1: we are stronger together. and i cannot wait to get my arm muscles back.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

column1: after 5 years in college and 2 Â½ gap years
column2: i am less than a month away from graduating and i honestly didnâ€™t think i would make it here. iâ€™m so close to finishing and last week i got one-step closer: i completed my senior art project

column1: i was assaulted twice before i turned 20. when i was 17 and a senior in high school i was raped by someone i cared deeply about. and when i was 19 and a freshman in college
many already know this because i speak so openly about it. casually even. thatâ€™s the only way i can wrap my head around this. as a joke. or as irony. at the same time
column2: iâ€™ve built up so many walls around myself to keep out the memories
column6: it feels like iâ€™m hiding behind a blade of grass.

column1: with the support of my friends and family i was able to sever ties with the friend from college. the trauma from the first one was harder to work through. this past february i sent him a letter describing the emotional trauma he has put me through.

that letter is what inspired my project. i have added quotes from this letter to a five piece fragmented self-portrait. it was definitely a risky move to blend the worst part of my past with the most important part of my academic career thus far but i feel like iâ€™m at a point where i can start trying to leave it behind.

iâ€™m not sharing this to make a statement or make anyone uncomfortable. i just want to point out that these situations are never black and white or what is expected from a rape case. in both situations
column5: never thought i had to protect myself from people i trusted the most with my heart and my body. so please

column1: please repost!  @voices_in_action was created by my amazing friend @iamjessicabarth  who is a #silencebreaker in the #metoo movement. her original website â€œwho is your harveyâ€ was integral in exposing a abusers that were then reported on in the press. the site has evolved and is now called voices in action (link in my bio) and will help to continue the clean up this town and world and unite survivors to help the healing process. ğŸ™ğŸ’›ğŸ‘Š
a new way to report sexual misconduct in the entertainment industry is here! .
itâ€™s been more than a year since #metoo turned into a global movement and yet
column2: little has changed. as time ticks on
column3: weâ€™re still left wondering - are we any less vulnerable from the abuses of power?  what do we actually do if we have been harassed or assaulted?  where can we report? @voices_in_action is a survivor-led organization that offers safe and confidential place to report incidents of sexual misconduct. we will also provide an alert if an assailant has been reported by more than one victim with the ability to connect through our team of attorneys under confidentiality and privilege. voices in action empowers survivors with the knowledge that they are not alone and their voice matters. itâ€™s time to turn awareness into action. i am #provoice. #voicesinaction to help support a safer
column4: more equitable and inclusive industry - please click link in bio. every little bit helps get us one step closer!

column1: 1) tuck your chin and shrug your shoulders. this will alleviate some of the pressure and make it hard for them to continue to squeeze.
2) use your hands as a shield to protect against knee strikes to your face as we do our escape. (simply x off your hands framing towards your attackers hips)
3) use your whole body weight to bow down towards the middle and circle your head out.
this technique emphasizes the concept of not trying to muscle our way out of something
column2: but instead figure out how to use your own body weight and leverage to escape. it's very similar to how we escape certain hand grips
column3: by finding the weakest spot of the grip and capitalizing on it to break free.

column1: 131608;instagram;2018-11-29 01:12:14;FALSE;"#metoo synchronicity // miracle report. tonight i got home from the gym. my mom was on the phone and she was talking to a friend about me- referencing one of my videos where i was speaking about cutting energetic chords to people and trauma. then she told this person about the story of how i was sexually abused as a child. this was so powerful to hear her tell my story. to hear her speak of how proud she is of me for overcoming the trauma. she then mentioned to her friend that when i finally told her for the first time
column2: the following day he messaged me on fb out of nowhere- crazy synchronicity- and shows how we are quantum entangled to people.

column1: in the moment she told this story- i heard god say to me- call him now. it was almost 11pm. it was so clear in that moment. i have been anticipating this phone call for years. i had previously researched his name and location and kept the info in a file- and tonight- i picked up the phone
column2: and i called my perpetrator- and had an hour long conversation with him. i will make a video about it soon. (i also recorded the entire convo on camera). i confronted him. i made him apologize (he denied he even did something in the beginning). i made sure he knew how fucked up it was. i explained the trauma
column5: and even suicide attempts. and then i forgave him > i asked if i could end the convo with a prayer - and i cut the energetic chords to him. my entire body was in goose bumps. i was doing energy work the entire time. it was beyond epic.

column2: ""do you want to set yourself free and heal your karma

column2: we remember sex workers who have died from violence. international day to end violence against sex workers was founded 15 years ago in san francisco by @anniesprinkled as a memorial and candlelight vigil for the victims of the seattle green river killer. the day calls attention to hate crimes committed against sex workers worldwide
column3: as well as the need to remove the stigma
column4: discrimination and indifference that contributes to violence against them. it is now observed globally in local vigils and gatherings.

column1: from the time i began my career in human sexuality
column2: the rights of sex workers has been my passion. in 1985
column3: a meeting took place at judson memorial church that connected me with margo st. james and the international sex workersâ€™ rights movement. i have been active in that movement ever since. judson memorial church has been a long-time advocate for harm reduction and safe haven for sex workers
column4: and the welcoming host of the nyc december 17 vigil for nearly a decade. i invite you to join me
column7: and friends and allies as we remember the dead. rest in power.

column2: and should always have a chance to expose abusers. but for all of the true abusers rightly exposed
column3: itâ€™s important to imagine the possibility that some individuals may also have been falsely accused. should individualsâ€™ identities be exposed before lawfully determined guilty? the court of public opinion isnâ€™t the same as a proper and fair trial... victims should always be heard
column4: but donâ€™t abusers and the innocent alike deserve a fair trial prior to public judgement? .

column1: 131656;instagram;2018-11-29 00:25:41;FALSE;"â€œthis year has been one of the worse of my life. and i could of changed it all if iâ€™d said â€œnoâ€. i was love in this time last year. and i truly believe he loved me as much as i loved him. in december 2017 i found out i was pregnant. and i was happy. i told my partner and he wasnâ€™t happy. he didnâ€™t shout/scream or swear just said he couldnâ€™t deal with having another child at the moment (was having an intense custody hearing with his first born
column2: which i had helped and supported him through). he promised me weâ€™d try again and that he wanted children with me but it wasnâ€™t the right time. like a fool in love
column3: i believed him and did something that felt wrong with every ounce of my being. 13th january 2018 my pregnancy ended. and when i tell you i hated myself and wanted off of this mortal coil
column4: iâ€™m not being over dramatic. and i did all of this without heâ€™s support because he couldnâ€™t deal with it. and couldnâ€™t either. but i put someoneâ€™s happiness before my own.

column2: he left me. the last time i saw him was the 12th january.

column3: iâ€™ve had to carry on with a broken heart and the guilt of knowing what iâ€™ve done.

column1: 131801;instagram;2018-11-28 21:34:34;FALSE;"this photo by #tornbergphotography is from a series called #deerwoman  #womaninaframe #objectification #art #photoart i've been working on for a few years. i became a model as a child. 15 years old in paris on my own and since then i have travelled and worked all over the world on my own. i became an actress
column2: then a self taught director and photographer. i have been financially independent since the age of 15. my romantic childhood dream of becoming an artist very soon became #thehauntinggame i have met them all
column3: all the men in the media and always felt like a haunted animal
column5: to be collected like a trophy
column7: objectified and sexualized. in the end you start to believe that you are just that
column9: and willingly hold up the frame. i have fought against this my whole life
column10: had a strong faith and integrity and have worked myself sick to prove to the world and myself that i am an artist
column11: that i never got anything for free
column12: afraid people didn't think i work for what i have
column15: assaulted and devalued. i became reclusive and afraid of the world until the ultimate crime against me was committed. and at the time i was healing from all that
column16: the truth about so many criminals came out and women started to speak their truth. i have been feeling so alone my whole life
column17: always thought there was something wrong with me for having been a target but hearing all the stories from other women made me cry in solidarity
column18: i was not alone. and as i'm healing i'm starting to wake up. the other night i woke up hearing the words from my subconscious whisper: ""you have been ruled by fear your whole life
column19: but you are starting to understand that it's not what was done to you that you fear the most

column1: 131979;instagram;2018-11-28 18:01:16;FALSE;"accepting another lonely christmas over this cup of tea. are you sans lover this holiday season? iâ€™ve had many years of this over the last 16 years. it can be difficult to be single around the holidays but there are ways that you can make the most of your singleness and still have a wonderful holiday season. this is how i will spend mine this year: service to others. it is the very best medicine for sadness or a broken heart. try it. .

try to dig deep and live outside of yourself this holiday season. whatever that means for you. find ways that you can help people less fortunate than yourself. there is a whole lot of that going on. no shortage of people in need. i for one

column3: i will be seeking out people in my life who are struggling and trying to comfort them in any way i can. .
